PARAGRAPH.#text: By Cassandra Sweet Of DOW JONES NEWSWIRES Michigan utility Consumers Energy said Friday it plans to spend $1.6 billion to cut pollution at its coal-fired power plants, including shutting some units, and it has scrapped plans to build a low-emission coal plant. Consumers Energy, owned by CMS Energy Corp. CMS, will have to cut emissions from its coal fleet to comply with new and pending federal and state limits on pollution from power plants. Meanwhile, slowing industrial demand for electricity in Michigan, which has been hit hard by the economic downturn, and low natural gas prices that make coal look expensive, prompted the company to reverse plans to build an 830-megawatt advanced coal plant that would have spewed fewer emissions than older coal technologies.

Headlines.Headline: CMS Looks Abroad for Profit

PARAGRAPH.#text:
CMS Energy
 is betting big on
countries with shoddy energy infrastructure. So far, the bets appear to be
paying off. CMS stock has outperformed the Dow Jones Utility Average since
1991, and with $4 billion of projects under way overseas, CMS is among the
few U.S. utility companies whose stock is seen as having above-average
growth potential.
